## Cryptographic Weakness Analysis

**Known Broken/Weak Algorithms and Their Attacks:**

### Hash Functions
| Algorithm | Status | Known Attacks |
|-----------|--------|---------------|
| MD5 | **BROKEN** | Collision attacks in seconds (Wang et al. 2004). Chosen-prefix collisions demonstrated (Stevens et al. 2009). HashClash tool generates collisions trivially. |
| SHA-1 | **BROKEN** | SHAttered attack (Google/CWI 2017) demonstrated practical collision. Cost: ~$110K in cloud compute (2019). Chosen-prefix collisions demonstrated (Leurent & Peyrin 2020). |
| MD4 | **BROKEN** | Collisions found in milliseconds. Completely broken since 2004. |
| RIPEMD | **WEAK** | Collision attacks demonstrated on original RIPEMD. RIPEMD-160 still theoretically secure but not recommended for new designs. |
| CRC32 | **NOT CRYPTO** | Not a cryptographic hash. Trivially reversible. Never use for security. |

### Symmetric Ciphers
| Algorithm | Status | Known Attacks |
|-----------|--------|---------------|
| DES | **BROKEN** | 56-bit key brute-forced in hours. Deep Crack (1998): 22 hours. |
| 3DES | **DEPRECATED** | Sweet32 birthday attack (2016). NIST deprecated after 2023. |
| RC4 | **BROKEN** | Statistical biases enable plaintext recovery (Royal Holloway 2013). Bar-Mitzvah attack. Prohibited in TLS since RFC 7465. |
| Blowfish | **WEAK** | 64-bit block size vulnerable to Sweet32. Not recommended for new designs. |
| ECB mode | **INSECURE** | Deterministic: identical plaintext blocks produce identical ciphertext. The ECB Penguin demonstrates the problem visually. |

### Password Hashing
| Algorithm | Status | Assessment |
|-----------|--------|------------|
| Plain MD5/SHA-* | **INSECURE** | GPU cracking: billions of hashes/second. Hashcat benchmarks available. |
| Unsalted hash | **INSECURE** | Rainbow table attacks. Pre-computed tables cover common passwords. |
| Single iteration | **INSECURE** | No key stretching. Falls to brute-force. |

